children.text: This is a simple paragraph, with some bullet points in it
Here is bullet point 2, with formatting such as
Now there are some h2, h3 and so on
, now I will add some more tags but sprinkle them among other elements such as
responsibility for actions by combatants in action, such as intentionally
, and for any individual that is part of the command structure who orders any attempt to committing
responsibility for actions by combatants in action, such as intentionally
, and for any individual that is part of the command structure who orders any attempt to committing

Enable indexing of external entities, and searching through them. For any given query, the search results should return all entities that match the query and the UI renders these results according to the type of entity matched.
We have the following entities. The fields are from a perspective of indexing
Primary Key, this is the entity ID. Prefix:
- Notes that this task is referenced in. Right now, a single task can be referred to only in one note, but we need to add support to allow tasks to be referenced in multiple notes
- Actions/Mentions/Tag IDs. For each entity, we would have an
field containing IDs of entities that this contains. For example, consider the task
is treated as an associated entity and the
- Alias of the user. Not sure if we are going to index it
, these blocks are parsed when parsing and saving content
- Title of the note this block belongs to
- Parsed text from the block. Different block types could have a different parsing logic, like the current
used when parsing ILinks, Excalidraw elements etc.
- Stores the preview of the block to display when showing search results
Same as blocks, just in a different index
Same as snippets, in a different index
: For searching through tags and mentions. Provides fuzzy search in objects (searches through a specific key) and plain strings
- Full text search with support for complex documents, partial matching and tags
For mentions and tags, since we do not have multiple fields, it makes sense to use fuzzy search instead of creating and maintaining a separate index
